# Tricks/DirectPlay.elm — WORKHORSE (the simplest trick)

DIRECT_PLAY: a hand card extends an existing board stack at
one of its ends. The floor of the trick system — if nothing
else is available, this one often is.

## Status

- **Label:** WORKHORSE. Stable, small.
- **Go counterpart ripped 2026-04-20.** Hints are client-side
  now (`project_hints_are_client_side.md`); this module stands
  alone on the Elm side.

## What it finds

For each hand card `hc` and each board stack `s`, tries
`rightMerge s single` and `leftMerge s single`. If either
works, emit a Play.

## Priority: right merge first

`mergeEitherSide` prefers right-merge when both would work.
Matches the canonical convention — runs grow naturally
rightward, so right-extend is the "default growth direction."
Swapping the order changes which Play the Hint engine picks
when multiple are valid for the same (hand-card, stack) pair.

## Apply-time safety

`applyDirectPlay` re-reads the stack at `targetIdx` and
re-runs `mergeEitherSide`. If the board has drifted and the
merge no longer validates, returns `(board, [])` — the
standard "refusal" pattern (see `Trick.claude`).

## Key exports

- `trick : Trick` — the plugin value. `id = "direct_play"`,
  description: "Play a hand card onto the end of a stack."

## What this module deliberately does NOT do

- **Extract from a stack.** End-peels are
  `Tricks.PeelForRun` / `Tricks.PairPeel`.
- **Handle hand-only groups.** That's `Tricks.HandStacks`.
- **Choose the target.** Emit one Play per target; ranking is
  the Hint engine's job.

## Pointers

- Python counterpart: `hints.direct_play` in
  `games/lynrummy/python/hints.py` (emits primitives, not
  Plays — different API, same game logic).
- Depends on: `CardStack.leftMerge`/`rightMerge`,
  `Tricks.Helpers`, `Tricks.Trick`.
- Consumer: `Tricks.Hint.hintPriorityOrder`.
